\section{Introduction}
\begin {frame}[shrink]
\begin{itemize}
	\item The World Wide Web is today's largest warehouse of knowledge.
\item Documents over the Web is largely unorganized.
\item  Web is accessible only for humans.
\item Computers understand only the Web pages' structure and layout and have no
access to their intended meaning.
\item The Semantic Web aims to enrich the existing
Web with a layer of machine interpretable meta data so that a computer program
can draw conclusions.

\end{itemize}
 	\begin{block}{Semantic Web Mining}
  Web Mining applies data mining techniques to Web.  \alert { Semantic Web Mining} aims
at combining the two emergent research areas,  Semantic Web and Web Mining.
	\end{block}
	\begin{center}
	\includegraphics[scale=0.27]{wmining.png}
\end{center}
\end{frame}
\section{Literature Survey}
\begin{frame}
\begin{block}{Tim Berners-Lee, 1999}
I have a dream for the Web in which computers become capable of analyzing all the data on the Web. The content, links, and transactions between people and computers. A 'Semantic Web', which should make this possible, has yet to emerge, but when it does, the day-to-day mechanisms of trade, bureaucracy and our daily lives will be handled by machines talking to machines
\end{block}
\begin{itemize}
	 \item The increasing interest in Web
information retrieval led to the Semantic Web initiative from the World-Wide Web Consortium.
\item The Semantic Web is the  manifestation of graph
theory and description logic.

\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
	\includegraphics[scale=0.33]{smlayercake.png}
	\captionof{figure}{Semantic Web Layer Cake}
	
\end{center}

\end {frame}
 \subsection{Research Scope}
\begin{frame}

 Web mining offers three areas 
 for  research 
\begin{itemize}
	\item Web usage mining : analyses the user behavior
         \item web structure mining: explores the hyper link structure
           \item Web content mining: exploits the contents of the documents in the web.
\end{itemize}      
   Among the three research areas, ontology approach is best suitable for Web content
mining . 
\begin{itemize}
	\item An ontology is an explicit specification of a conceptualization
.
\item In computer science, the word ontology, borrowed from philosophy, represents a set of
precisely defined terms (vocabulary) about a specific domain 
\item An ontology  enables people to agree upon the meaning of terms used in a 
domain.

\end{itemize}     
  \end{frame}
\section{Semantic Web Technologies: State of The Art }
\begin{frame}

 \begin{itemize}
 

  
\item Two aspects of Semantic Web programming:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item Information Modeling 
\item  Application level integration
\end{enumerate}
  
\item   Information Modeling  can be broken into two subproblems:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item Syntax sharing problem 
          \item Semantic sharing problem.
\end{enumerate}

\item Finding a common medium
for communication is analogous to the syntactic aspect of sharing data.


\item Finding a mutually intelligible encoding of concepts within the
common medium is analogous to the semantic data-sharing problem.
\item The combination of data and metadata solves  the information sharing
problem at the semantic level.

\end{itemize}
 \end{frame} 
\subsection{The Semantic Web Information Model : RDF}
\begin{frame}

 \begin{itemize}
\item Resource Description Framework is the data
model used by the Semantic Web
 \item In RDF, information is represented as a set of assertions called
statements made up of three parts: subject, predicate, and object (triples).
\item In RDF, resources can represent anything that can be named. A resource is,
in fact, nothing but a name that represents an object, act, or concept.
\item Resource names take the form of Internationalized Resource Identifiers.
  \end{itemize}
\begin{center}
	\includegraphics[scale=0.35]{2-1.png}
	
\end{center}

