\end{center}


 \end{frame}
\subsection{RDF Serializations}
\begin{frame}

\begin{center}
	\includegraphics[scale=0.25]{2-4.png}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
	\item RDF graphs are powerful tools for representing information, but they are
 good for human analysis unsuitable for application exchange.
\item Serialization makes RDF practical for information exchange by providing a
way to convert between the abstract model and a concrete format, such as
a file or other byte stream.
\item Three of the most popular RDF Serialization formats  are:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item  RDF/XML
\item Terse RDF Triple
Language (Turtle)
\item  N-Triples
\end{enumerate}


 \end{itemize}
                 
\end{frame}


\subsection{Expressing Semantics in RDF}
\begin{frame}


\begin{itemize}
	\item To add meaning to RDF graphs,  needs
some means of defining a vocabulary of predefined terms with accompanying
semantics for describing the information.
\item The Semantic Web uses a combination of a schema language and an
ontology language to provide the capabilities of vocabularies, taxonomies, and
ontologies.
\item RDF Schema (RDFS) provides a specific vocabulary for RDF that
can be used to define taxonomies of classes and properties and simple domain
and range specifications for properties.
\item RDFS vocabularies describe the classes of resources and properties being
used in an RDF model.

 \end{itemize} 
\begin{center}
	\includegraphics[scale=0.30]{2-6.png}
\end{center}               
\end{frame}
\subsection{Ontology}
\begin{frame}


\begin{itemize}
	\item The term Ontology ( Greek words onto for existence,  and logos for science)

\item The key role that ontologies are likely to play in the future of the Web has led to the extension of Web markup languages.
\item  In the context of the Semantic Web, an ontology language should:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item be compatible with existing Web standards
\item define terms precisely and formally with adequate expressive power
\item be easy to understand and use
\item provide automated reasoning support 
\item provide richer service descriptions which could be interpreted by intelligent agents
\item be sharable across applications.


\end{enumerate}
\end {itemize}
                 
\end{frame}



\subsection{OWL}
\begin{frame}


\begin{itemize}
	\item W3C has designed the Web Ontology Language
\item  It is built on W3C standards RDF/RDFS  and extends these languages with richer modeling primitives.
\item  It is a revision of the DAML+OIL

\item OWL allows:
\begin{itemize}
	\item the formalization of a domain by defining classes and properties of those classes, 
\item the definition of individuals and the assertion of properties about them, and 
\item the reasoning about these classes and individuals.
\end{itemize}
\item OWL, layered on top of RDFS, extends RDFS capabilities.
\item OWL adds various constructors for building complex class expressions, cardinality restrictions on properties, characteristics of properties and mapping between classes and individuals 
\item  An ontology in OWL is a set of axioms describing classes, properties and facts about individuals.



\end {itemize}
                 
\end{frame}

\subsection{Querying The Semantic Web}
\begin{frame}


\begin{itemize}
	\item Querying the Semantic Web requires a language that recognizes RDF 
\item  SPARQL is a recursive acronym for SPARQL Protocol
and RDF Query Language 
\item  An RDF data store is a special database system built for the
storage and retrieval of RDF statements.
\item 
A SPARQL endpoint can be understood as an interface that users (human or application)
can access to query an RDF data store by using SPARQL query language.
\item SPARQL provides four different forms of query:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item SELECT query
\item ASK query
\item DESCRIBE query
\item CONSTRUCT query

\end{enumerate}

\end {itemize}
                 
\end{frame}
\section{Research Aim and Objectives}
\begin{frame}


\begin{block}{Research Aim and Objectives}
	  Aim of this paper is to formulate an automated information retrieval
system prototype which provides semantic web visualization environment  as an interface and uses various
Semantic Web mechanisms in order to provide relevant information to end users or communities of
users. To achieve this goal, Web pages must be annotated, using the terms defined in an ontology.
Once the pages are semantically annotated, agents/applications  uses existing meta data and inference engines to
answer queries.
\end{block}


        
\begin{center}
	\includegraphics[scale=0.28]{project1.png}
	\captionof{figure}{Prototype an Abstract View}
	\end{center}  

\end{frame}
\subsection{Architecture }
\begin{frame}
\begin{itemize}
	\item Starting from a textual search, the user is presented with a rich aggregate of information about the entity likely identified
with the query.
\item  Queries can be about people whose  FOAF Ontology based  annotation published  on the Semantic Web 
\item As the user visualizes the aggregate, he can follow links to other properties, switching the focus of visualization to that of neighboring entities.
\end{itemize}

 

